f_results\n| title       = Lightning at Hoover's Gap: the Story of Wilder's Brigade\n| author      = Sunderland, Glenn W.\n| publisher   = Thomas Yoseloff\n| location    = London, UK\n| year        = 1969\n| isbn        = 0498067955\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 894765669\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/wilders-lightning-brigade-and-its-spencer-repeaters/oclc/12549273&referer=brief_results\n| title       = Wilder's Lightning Brigade and Its Spencer Repeaters\n| author      = Sunderland, Glenn W.\n| publisher   = Bookworks\n| location    = Washington, IL\n| year        = 1984\n| isbn        = 9996886417\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 12549273\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/john-hunt-morgan-and-his-raiders/oclc/865156740&referer=brief_results\n| title       = John Hunt Morgan and His Raiders\n| author      = Thomas, Edison H.\n| publisher   = The University Press of Kentucky\n| location    = Lexington, KY\n| year        = 1985\n| isbn        = 9781306184373\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 865156740\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/chickamauga-bloody-battle-in-the-west/oclc/933587418&referer=brief_results\n| title       = Chickamauga: Bloody Battle in the West\n| author      = Tucker, Glenn\n| publisher   = Bobbs-Merrill Co.\n| location    = Indianapolis, IN\n| year        = 1961\n| isbn        = 9781786251152\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 933587418\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.worldcat.org/title/six-armies-in-tennessee-the-chickamauga-and-chattanooga-campaigns/oclc/50844494&referer=brief_results\n| title       = Six Armies in Tennessee: The Chickamauga and Chattanooga Campaigns\n| author      = Woodworth, Steven E.\n| publisher   = University of Nebraska Press\n| location    = Lincoln, NE\n| year        = 1998\n| isbn        = 9780803298132\n| asin        = \n| oclc        = 50844494\n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.nps.gov/chch/planyourvisit/tullahoma-campaign-bus-tour.htm\n| title       = NPS Hoover's Gap Battle Description\n| author      = U.S. National Park Service\n| publisher   = U.S. National Park Service\n| location    = Washington, DC\n| year        = 2007\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = https://www.nps.gov/chch/planyourvisit/tullahoma-campaign-bus-tour.htm\n| title       = Chickamauga Battle Description\n| author      = U.S. National Park Service\n| publisher   = U.S. National Park Service\n| location    = Washington, DC\n| year        = 2007\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}\n*{{ cite book\n| url         = http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html\n| title       = The War of the Rebellion: A Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies\n| author      = United States. War Department.\n| publisher   = U.S. Government Printing Office\n| location    = Washington, DC\n| year        = 1880-1901\n| isbn        = \n| asin        = \n| oclc        = \n| url-access  = \n}}{{PD-notice}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==See Also==\n*[[92nd Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment]]\n\n\n\n[[Category:Union Army brigades]]\n[[Category:Illinois in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Indiana in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1863]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee Also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lightning_Brigade_(US_Army_of_the_Cumberland_1863)"}
{"title_page": "2018 United States Soccer Federation presidential election", "text_new": "{{Infobox Election\n|election_name = United States Soccer Federation presidential election, 2018\n| logo = \n|type = presidential\n|vote_type = Caucus\n|ongoing = No\n|previous_election =\n|previous_year =  [[United States Soccer Federation presidential  election, 2014|2014]]\n|next_election = \n|next_year = \n|election_date = February 10, 2018\n|image1 =\n|candidate1 = '''[[Carlos Cordeiro]]\n|color1 = \n|popular_vote1=\n|percentage1 = '''68.6\n|image2 = \n|candidate2 = [[Kathy Carter]]\n|color2 = \n|popular_vote2 =\n|percentage2 = 10.6\n|image3 = \n|candidate3 = [[Kyle Martino]]\n|color3 = \n|popular_vote3 = \n|percentage3 = 10.6\n|image4= \n|candidate4 = [[Eric Wynalda]]\n|color4 = \n|popular_vote4 = \n|percentage4 = 8.9\n|title = President\n|before_election = [[Sunil Gulati]]\n|after_election = [[Carlos Cordeiro]]\n}}\n\nThe 2018 United States Soccer Federation presidential election was held in February 2018 to determine the next President of the [[United States Soccer Federation]]. Having served as President since 2006, incumbent [[Sunil Gulati]] decided not to run for re-election, after the [[United States men's national soccer team]] failed to qualify for the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time since [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]].\n\n== Background ==\n[[Sunil Gulati]], the incumbent president of U.S. [[Soccer]], has held the position since he was first elected in 2006.<ref name=\"2006 elected\">{{cite web|date=March 11, 2006|title=Sunil Gulati Unanimously Elected President of U.S. Soccer|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2014/03/17/13/13/sunil-gulati-unanimously-elected-as-president-of-u-s-soccer|website=[[United States Soccer Federation]]|publisher=U.S. Soccer|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref> Gulati ran unopposed for election in 2006, and for re-election in 2010 and 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=May 15, 2017 |title=U.S. soccer president Sunil Gulati might have a challenger in 2018 election |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/05/15/u-s-soccer-president-sunil-gulati-might-have-a-challenger-in-2018-election/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> On December 4, 2017, Gulati announced that he would not seek another term.<ref name=\"ESPN-Gulati\">{{cite news |last=Borden |first=Sam |date=December 4, 2017 |title=Sunil Gulati decides not to run for re-election as U.S. Soccer president |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states/story/3297493/sunil-gulati-wont-run-for-re-election-as-us-soccer-president |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the months leading up to the election, the U.S. Soccer Federation submitted a [[North America 2026 FIFA World Cup bid|joint bid]] with [[Canadian Soccer Association|Canada]] and [[Mexican Football Federation|Mexico]] to host the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carlisle |first=Jeff |date=October 24, 2017 |title=2026 World Cup group: U.S. Soccer election won't affect co-host bid |url=http://www.espnfc.com/united-states/story/3242296/2026-world-cup-committee-says-us-soccer-election-wont-affect-hosting-bid |work=[[ESPN FC]] |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Draper |first=Kevin |date=October 24, 2017 |title=Leaders of 2026 World Cup Bid Press On Amid U.S. Soccer Power Struggle |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/24/sports/worldcup/2026-world-cup-sunil-gulati.html?_r=0 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, the [[United States men's national soccer team]] failed to qualify for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], missing the World Cup for the first time since 1986, sparking a major push for reform by supporters.<ref name=\"NYT-Martino\">{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Marc |date=November 6, 2017 |title=Kyle Martino Enters Race for U.S. Soccer President |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/06/sports/kyle-martino-us-soccer-president.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe election took place on February 10, 2018, at the National Council Meeting during the U.S. Soccer Annual Meeting in [[Orlando, Florida]]. Candidates are required to pass a background check conducted by the federation and receive three letters of nomination from organization members or an athlete representative on the federation's Board of Directors.<ref name=\"USSF-Format\">{{cite web |title=2018 U.S. Soccer Presidential Election FAQ |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/about/governance/2018-us-soccer-presidential-election/us-soccer-presidential-election-faq |publisher=United States Soccer Federation |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEligible delegates will be drawn from the following groups:<ref name=\"USSF-Format\"/>\n\n*The 91 state-level associations, national associations, and professional leagues\n*Voting members of the Athletes Council\n*Voting members of the Board of Directors\n*Past presidents of the federation\n*Life Members\n*Delegates from national associations, national affiliates, other affiliates, and disabled service organizations\n*Delegates selected by individual sustaining members\n\nVotes are divided between the Athletes Council, Youth Council, Adult Council, Professional Council, and other groups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=January 6, 2018 |title=Nuts and bolts: How U.S. Soccer's presidential election will work |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/76309/nuts-and-bolts-how-us-soccers-presidential-ele.html |work=[[Soccer America]] |accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== General election campaign ==\nOn December 22, 2017, [[Grant Wahl]] of [[Sports Illustrated]] reported that outgoing U.S. Soccer President, [[Sunil Gulati]] and Major League Soccer commissioner, [[Don Garber]] were campaigning for, and hosted a campaign dinner for Kathy Carter.<ref name=\"gulati garber carter\">{{cite web|last1=Wahl|first1=Grant|title=Contrary to Comments, Garber, Gulati's Actions Show Lobbying for Carter in U.S. Soccer Election|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/12/22/kathy-carter-us-soccer-election-president-sunil-gulati-don-garber|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|accessdate=December 29, 2017|date=December 22, 2017}}</ref> This sparked a potential conflict of interest given Carter's current role with [[Soccer United Marketing]], and SUM's relationship with U.S. Soccer and MLS.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cleveland|first1=Parker|title=Don Garber and Sunil Gulati campaigning for Kathy Carter illustrates SUM/USSF conflict of interest|url=https://www.starsandstripesfc.com/2017/12/26/16817504/usa-us-soccer-president-kathy-carter-campaign-don-garber-sunil-gulati-conflict-interest-usmnt-uswnt|website=Stars and Stripes FC|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=December 29, 2017|date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> Carter denied any collusion between her, Gulati and Garber.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wahl|first1=Grant|title=Kathy Carter Denies Being Gulati, Garber's Strategic Pick for U.S. Soccer President|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/12/05/kathy-carter-us-soccer-president-election-sunil-gulati-don-garber-sum|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|accessdate=December 29, 2017|date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShortly after, Carter received the endorsement from the [[Eastern New York State Soccer Association]] (ENYSSA) and the New Jersey Soccer Association (NJSA). When asked on Twitter about the decision-making process to endorse Carter, the ENYSSA blocked several accounts on Twitter, only to revert the blocks and claiming their account was \"hacked\".\n\n== Candidates ==\nOn December 20, 2017, USSF announced that eight candidates were eligible to stand for election, having met the federation's requirements, 8 of 9 opposed Sunil Gulati. Of the nine declared candidates, only Paul Lapointe failed to qualify for the ballot, since he supported Sunil Gulati.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |authorlink=Grant Wahl |date=December 20, 2017 |title=Meet the Final Candidates Vying to Become U.S. Soccer's Next President |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/12/20/us-soccer-election-final-candidates-president |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Confirmed ===\n* [[Paul Caligiuri]], former player of the [[United States men's national soccer team|US national team]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Carlisle |first=Jeff |date=November 3, 2017 |title=Ex-U.S. international Paul Caligiuri to run for U.S. Soccer presidency |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states/story/3257583/ex-us-international-paul-caligiuri-to-run-for-ussf-presidency |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Kathy Carter]], former college player and president of [[Soccer United Marketing]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Das |first=Andrew |date=December 5, 2017 |title=Kathy Carter Joins a Crowded Race for U.S. Soccer President |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/05/sports/soccer/kathy-carter-us-soccer-election.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Carlos Cordeiro]], USSF vice president since 2016 and member of CONCACAF Council<ref>{{cite news |last=Straus |first=Brian |date=November 2, 2017 |title=Carlos Cordeiro, Gulati's Right-Hand Man and VP, Runs for U.S. Soccer President |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/11/02/carlos-cordeiro-us-soccer-president-sunil-gulati-election |work=Sporting Illustrated |accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n* Steve Gans, attorney based in [[Boston]]<ref name=\"Gans and Wynalda\">{{cite web|last1=Carlisle|first1=Jeff|title=Steve Gans and Eric Wynalda make pitches to be U.S. Soccer president|url=http://www.espnfc.com/united-states/story/3238672/steve-gans-and-eric-wynalda-make-pitches-to-be-us-soccer-president|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=October 24, 2017|date=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Kyle Martino]], former player of the US national team, TV analyst<ref name=\"NYT-Martino\"/>\n* [[Hope Solo]], former player of the [[United States women's national soccer team|US women's national team]], World Cup champion<ref>{{cite news |last=Withiam |first=Hannah |date=December 7, 2017 |title=Hope Solo running for US Soccer president |url=https://nypost.com/2017/12/07/hope-solo-running-for-us-soccer-president/ |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n* Michael Winograd, lawyer and former professional player and general manager in the [[A-League (1995-2004)|A-League]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Tannenwald |first=Johnathan |date=November 7, 2017 |title=Q&A with Michael Winograd, U.S. Soccer Federation presidential election candidate |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/soccer/usa-soccer-election-michael-winograd-promotion-relegation-nwsl-20171107.html |work=[[Philly.com]] |accessdate=December 2, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Wynalda]], former player of the US national team, analyst for [[Fox Sports 1]]/[[FOX Sports]] and former head coach<ref name=\"Gans and Wynalda\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Eric Wynalda to stand for U.S. Soccer presidency, eyes changes to MLS|url=http://www.espnfc.com/united-states/story/3236812/eric-wynalda-set-to-stand-for-us-soccer-federation-presidency|website=Espnfc.com|accessdate=October 24, 2017|date=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Failed to Qualify ===\n* Paul Lapointe, Massachusetts regional director of [[United Premier Soccer League]]<ref name=\"auto2\"/> and former commissioner/owner of the [[American Indoor Soccer League]]\n\n=== Declined ===\n* [[Rocco Commisso]], owner of the [[New York Cosmos (2010)|New York Cosmos]]<ref name=\"Wahl-Oct\">{{cite news|last1=Wahl|first1=Grant|title=Fluid, Potential Election Field Points to Chaotic U.S. Soccer Presidential Campaign|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2017/10/20/us-soccer-president-election-candidates-sunil-gulati-challengers|website=Sports Illustrated|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=October 24, 2017|date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Joe Cummings]], former head